│ samesign attribute)\n\nWhen `%x = 0x8000000000000000` (INT64_MIN), `%cmp2`  │
│ becomes poison because the samesign attribute requires both operands to     │
│ have the same sign, but comparing INT64_MIN with 10 violates this           │
│ condition. However, `%cmp1` evaluates to false (0) normally.\n\nThe         │
│ original select returns 0 when `%cond = true`, but the transformed xor      │
│ returns poison because it directly uses the poison value from               │
│ `%cmp2`.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\n\nThe log shows that InstCombine     │
│ identifies the select instruction and applies the transformation at line    │
│ 4158 in InstCombineSelect.cpp: `return BinaryOperator::CreateXor(CondVal,   │
│ FalseVal);`. This happens because `isKnownInversion(FalseVal, TrueVal)`     │
│ returns true, incorrectly assuming these icmp instructions are logical      │
│ inverses.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n\nThe root cause is in the            │
│ `isKnownInversion` function (lines 8517-8536 in InstCombineSelect.cpp).     │
│ This function only checks if the predicates are inverses and if the         │
│ constant ranges match, but it completely ignores the 'samesign' attribute   │
│ of icmp instructions.\n\nSpecifically:\n- `%cmp1` uses `ICMP_ULT` with      │
│ RHS=11\n- `%cmp2` uses `ICMP_UGT` with RHS=10 and hasSameSign()=true\n\nThe │
│ function correctly identifies that `ULT` and `UGT` with constants 11 and 10 │
│ are inverses in terms of their constant ranges (`[0,11)` vs `[11,2^64)`),   │
│ but it fails to account for the fact that `%cmp2` can produce poison values │
│ due to the samesign attribute, while `%cmp1` cannot.\n\nTwo icmp            │
│ instructions with different samesign attributes cannot be considered true   │
│ logical inverses because they have different poison semantics.\n\n4.        │
│ Proposed Edit Point(s):\n\nThe fix is to modify the `isKnownInversion`      │
│ function to check that both icmp instructions have the same samesign        │
│ attribute before considering them as inverses. If one has samesign and the  │
│ other doesn't, they cannot be treated as logical inverses due to their      │
│ different poison behavior.\n\nEdit point:                                   │
